I now have a thorough picture of everything. Let me compile the full findings.

---

## Review: Editor Component Code Reuse Issues

Reviewing the 7 files at `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\`.

---

## Critical Issues

None found. All issues below are code quality / maintainability concerns.

---

## Important Issues

### 1. Duplicate `ErrorBoundary` class - Editor.jsx and RichTextEditor.jsx

**Confidence: 95**

Both files define an identical class-based `ErrorBoundary`:

`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\Editor.jsx` lines 12-23:
```jsx
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = { error: null };
  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    return { error };
  }
  render() {
    if (this.state.error) {
      return <div>Error: {this.state.error.message}</div>;
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\RichTextEditor.jsx` lines 30-41: identical body.

No shared `ErrorBoundary` exists anywhere else in `client/src` (no `shared/` or `common/` component directory). The rest of the codebase uses `LexicalErrorBoundary` from `@lexical/react` for the `RichTextPlugin` `ErrorBoundary` prop — which is what `RichTextEditor.jsx` already uses on line 273. The custom class in `RichTextEditor.jsx` is **defined but never used as a JSX wrapper** in that file. `Editor.jsx` uses its copy to wrap `<EditorInner>`. These should be extracted into a single shared file, e.g. `client/src/components/HomePage/Editor/EditorErrorBoundary.jsx`, and the dead copy in `RichTextEditor.jsx` should be deleted.

---

### 2. Unused local `theme` object in RichTextEditor.jsx

**Confidence: 100**

`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\RichTextEditor.jsx` lines 44-47:
```js
const theme = {
    paragraph: 'editor-paragraph',
    heading: 'editor-heading',
}
```

This variable is never referenced anywhere in the file. The actual theme used by the `LexicalComposer` at the `App.jsx` level comes from `EDITOR_THEME` in `editorConfig.js` — which is far more complete (includes heading variants h1/h2/h3, quote, lists, code, links, etc.). This is dead code and should be deleted.

---

### 3. Three independent `formatTimeAgo` / `timeAgo` / `formatDate` implementations for the same relative-time pattern

**Confidence: 95**

Three separate files each implement the same relative-time-ago logic with no shared utility:

- `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\RichTextEditor.jsx` lines 49-57 (`formatTimeAgo` — accepts a `Date` object, maxes out at hours)
- `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\DashboardBriefing\PromptResponsesModal.jsx` lines 8-17 (`timeAgo` — accepts a date string, extends to days/localeDateString)
- `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\DraftList\DraftList.jsx` lines 53-65 (`formatDate` — accepts a date string, extends to days/7-day cutoff)

All three implement the same `seconds → minutes → hours → (days)` branching pattern. There is no shared date utility in `client/src/utils/`. These should be consolidated into a single `client/src/utils/formatTimeAgo.js` export. The `RichTextEditor.jsx` version is also the weakest — it stops at hours and accepts a `Date` object while the other two accept ISO strings.

---

### 4. `.toolbar-bttns` and `.is-active` share almost all properties

**Confidence: 90**

`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\editor.css` lines 224-259:

```css
.toolbar-bttns {
    display: flex;
    width: fit-content;
    height: fit-content;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 6px;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all 0.15s ease;
    user-select: none;
    color: var(--editor-text);
}
/* ... */
.is-active {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    width: fit-content;
    height: fit-content;
    padding: 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 6px;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all 0.15s ease;
    user-select: none;
    background-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--editor-accent) 15%, transparent);
}
```

10 out of 11 properties on `.is-active` are identical to `.toolbar-bttns`. The only difference is the `background-color` (and the svg fill). A base class (`.toolbar-btn-base`) should be shared, with `.is-active` only overriding the background and color. Note that the mobile override at line 1108 already uses both in one selector (`toolbar-bttns, .is-active`), confirming they are treated as variants of the same element.

---

### 5. `.editor-save-bttn` / `.editor-save-bttn-disabled` and `.editor-draft-bttn` / `.editor-draft-bttn-disabled` share most properties

**Confidence: 88**

`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\editor.css`:

- Lines 455-492: `.editor-save-bttn` and `.editor-save-bttn-disabled` share `display: flex`, `justify-content: center`, `align-items: center`, `padding: 0.5rem 1.25rem`, `border-radius: 15px`, `font-weight: 650`, `border: none`. The disabled variant only differs in `background-color`, `color`, `cursor`, and removes transitions.
- Lines 495-535: Same pattern for `.editor-draft-bttn` / `.editor-draft-bttn-disabled` — they share `display: flex`, `justify-content: center`, `align-items: center`, `padding: 0.5rem 1rem`, `border-radius: 15px`, `font-weight: 600`, `border: 1.5px solid var(--editor-border)`, `font-size: 0.875rem`.

This also manifests in the mobile overrides at lines 1130-1145 where all four class names are listed separately with the same override values.

The conventional fix is a shared `.editor-btn` base class with modifier classes (or CSS `[disabled]` selectors) handling only the state differences.

---

### 6. Seven resize handle classes duplicate the same base properties

**Confidence: 85**

`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\editor.css` lines 603-689. Every one of the 7 resize handle classes (`.southeast-side-handle`, `.southwest-side-handle`, `.northeast-side-handle`, `.northwest-side-handle`, `.east-side-handle`, `.south-side-handle`, `.north-side-handle`) declares:

```css
position: absolute;
background-color: var(--bg-pill);
border: 1px solid var(--editor-text);
border-radius: /* 50% or 2px */;
z-index: 10;
```

Only `position` offset, `width`, `height`, `border-radius`, `cursor`, and centering transforms differ per handle. A shared `.resize-handle` base class with per-handle classes as modifiers would eliminate ~40 lines of duplication and make future theme changes to handle appearance a single-line edit.

---

### 7. `getTopLevelElement` logic duplicated three times in Toolbar.jsx

**Confidence: 90**

`C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\Editor\Toolbar.jsx` has the same try/catch block to get the top-level element repeated verbatim in three separate functions:

Lines 164-171 (update listener):
```js
let element;
try {
    element = anchorNode.getKey() === 'root'
        ? anchorNode
        : anchorNode.getTopLevelElement() || anchorNode.getTopLevelElementOrThrow();
} catch {
    element = null;
}
```

Lines 275-283 (`setHeading`):
```js
let element;
try {
    element = anchorNode.getKey() === 'root'
        ? anchorNode
        : anchorNode.getTopLevelElement() || anchorNode.getTopLevelElementOrThrow();
} catch (e) {
    console.error('Could not get top level element:', e);
    return;
}
```

Lines 316-324 (`setQuote`): identical to `setHeading`.

This should be extracted into a module-level helper function at the top of `Toolbar.jsx`:

```js
function getTopLevelElementSafe(anchorNode) {
    try {
        return anchorNode.getKey() === 'root'
            ? anchorNode
            : anchorNode.getTopLevelElement() || anchorNode.getTopLevelElementOrThrow();
    } catch {
        return null;
    }
}
```

Note the error handling behavior is slightly inconsistent between copies: the update listener silently returns `null` on failure, while `setHeading`/`setQuote` log to `console.error`. The extracted helper should standardize this.

---

